t: str\n    priority: TaskPriority = TaskPriority.NORMAL\n\n\ndef task_from_row(row) -> Task:\n    \"\"\"Build a Task from a sqlite3.Row.\"\"\"\n    keys = row.keys() if hasattr(row, \"keys\") else []\n    priority = TaskPriority(row[\"priority\"]) if \"priority\" in keys else TaskPriority.NORMAL\n    return Task(\n        id=row[\"id\"],\n        title=row[\"title\"],\n        status=TaskStatus(row[\"status\"]),\n        owner_id=row[\"owner_id\"],\n        created_at=row[\"created_at\"],\n        priority=priority,\n    )\n","numLines":41,"startLine":1,"totalLines":41}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-5","id":"msg_0129xJGmqnqfhx8inDbDsTf5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The Task model already exposes `priority`, so the API response (`/tasks`) presumably includes it. Here's the answer.\n\n## 1. Location\n\n- **`webclient/scripts/export_tasks.js`**\n  - `formatTaskRow(task)` (line 7) — assembles a single row: builds the `[id, status, title]` array and joins it with `\\t`. This is where you add the new field (e.g. `task.priority`) to the array.\n  - The `join('\\t')` inside `formatTaskRow` is also where the **column order is decided** — the array order *is* the column order. There's no separate header row or column-order config; the order is implicit in the literal array `[task.id, status, title]`.\n\n## 2. Mechanism / fix\n\n`TaskExporter.exportTsv` (same file, line 27) just calls `formatTaskRow` per task and writes the line — it doesn't know about individual fields, so no change needed there.\n\nTo add a column (e.g. task priority, which the API already returns per `pyserver/models/task.py`'s `Task.priority`/`TaskPriority` and `task_from_row`):\n\n- Edit `formatTaskRow` to include the new value in the returned array, e.g.:\n  `return [task.id, status, title, task.priority].join('\\t');`\n- Place it wherever the desired column position is — the array position = the TSV column position, since there's no header row or schema elsewhere enforcing order.\n\nNo other file needs to change unless the API (`pyserver/routes/tasks.py`) doesn't already serialize `priority` on `/tasks` — worth a quick check there if the field isn't present in the JSON response."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":642,"cache_read_input_tokens":35637,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":642},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null